  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How many different numbers of 4 digits can be made out of the digits 0,1,2,3,4,5, such that no digit is repeated?",
  "response": "To determine how many different 4-digit numbers can be formed using the digits **0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5** without repeating any digit, we'll follow these steps:\n\n### **Step 1: Identify the Total Number of Available Digits**\nWe have **6** distinct digits: **0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5**.\n\n### **Step 2: Determine the Position Constraints for a 4-Digit Number**\n- **First Digit (Thousands Place):**\n  - It **cannot** be **0** (since that would make it a 3-digit number).\n  - **Choices:** **1, 2, 3, 4, 5** \u2192 **5** options.\n  \n- **Second Digit (Hundreds Place):**\n  - Can be **any** of the remaining **5** digits (including **0** but excluding the first digit).\n  \n- **Third Digit (Tens Place):**\n  - Can be **any** of the remaining **4** digits.\n  \n- **Fourth Digit (Ones Place):**\n  - Can be **any** of the remaining **3** digits.\n\n### **Step 3: Apply the Counting Principle**\nMultiply the number of choices for each position:\n\\[\n\\begin{align*}\n\\text{First Digit} & : 5 \\text{ options} \\\\\n\\text{Second Digit} & : 5 \\text{ options} \\\\\n\\text{Third Digit} & : 4 \\text{ options} \\\\\n\\text{Fourth Digit} & : 3 \\text{ options} \\\\\n\\end{align*}\n\\]\n\\[\n\\text{Total 4-Digit Numbers} = 5 \\times 5 \\times 4 \\times 3\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\text{Total} = 5 \\times 5 \\times 4 \\times 3 = 300\n\\]\n\nAlternatively, using permutations:\n\n- **Total permutations** of 4 digits from 6:\n\\[\nP(6,4) = 6 \\times 5 \\times 4 \\times 3 = 360\n\\]\n  \n- **Subtract permutations where 0 is the first digit:**\n\\[\n\\text{If first digit is 0, then the next three digits are chosen from 5 options:}\nP(5,3) = 5 \\times 4 \\times 3 = 60\n\\]\n  \n- **Total valid 4-digit numbers:**\n\\[\n360 - 60 = 300\n\\]\n\n### **Final Answer**\n\\[\n\\boxed{300}\n\\]",
  "temperature": 1.0,
